<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<p class="p">The bivariate copulas are commonly used to describe the dependence between two random variables and to calculate the joint probability of an event. The joint probability distribution function 
 <italic class="italic">F</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">X</italic>,
  <italic class="italic">Y</italic>
 </sub>(
 <italic class="italic">x</italic>, 
 <italic class="italic">y</italic>) of random variables 
 <italic class="italic">X</italic> and 
 <italic class="italic">Y</italic> can be expressed as
 <disp-formula id="E1" class="disp-formula">
  <math id="m1" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">F</mi>
      <mrow class="mrow">
       <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">X</mi>
       <mo class="mo">,</mo>
       <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">Y</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">x</mi>
     <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">y</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">)</mo>
     <mo class="mo">=</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">P</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">X</mi>
     <mo class="mo">≤</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">x</mi>
     <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">Y</mi>
     <mo class="mo">≤</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">y</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
  <label class="label">(1)</label>
 </disp-formula>where 
 <italic class="italic">P</italic> is the joint cumulative probability. The marginal cumulative distribution functions are given by 
 <italic class="italic">F</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">X</italic>
 </sub>(
 <italic class="italic">x</italic>) = 
 <italic class="italic">P</italic>(
 <italic class="italic">X</italic> ≤ 
 <italic class="italic">x</italic>) and 
 <italic class="italic">F</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">Y</italic>
 </sub>(
 <italic class="italic">y</italic>) = 
 <italic class="italic">P</italic>(
 <italic class="italic">Y</italic> ≤ 
 <italic class="italic">y</italic>). Here, we used a copula function 
 <italic class="italic">C</italic> to describe a bivariate distribution function, so the joint probability distribution of 
 <italic class="italic">X</italic> and 
 <italic class="italic">Y</italic> can be written as
 <disp-formula id="E2" class="disp-formula">
  <math id="m2" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">F</mi>
      <mrow class="mrow">
       <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">X</mi>
       <mo class="mo">,</mo>
       <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">Y</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">x</mi>
     <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">y</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">)</mo>
     <mo class="mo">=</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">C</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">[</mo>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">F</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">X</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">x</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">)</mo>
     <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">F</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">Y</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">y</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">)</mo>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">]</mo>
     <mo class="mo">=</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">C</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">u</mi>
     <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">v</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">)</mo>
     <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     <mn class="mn">0</mn>
     <mo class="mo">≤</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">u</mi>
     <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">v</mi>
     <mo class="mo">≤</mo>
     <mn class="mn">1</mn>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
  <label class="label">(2)</label>
 </disp-formula>where the two marginal cumulative distribution functions are transformed into two uniformly distributed random variables 
 <italic class="italic">u</italic> and 
 <italic class="italic">v</italic> (i.e., the normalized ranks of 
 <italic class="italic">x</italic> and 
 <italic class="italic">y</italic>). As an example, the probability of an event, such as the variables exceed or are below given thresholds, can be expressed as
 <disp-formula id="E3" class="disp-formula">
  <math id="m3" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">p</mi>
     <mo class="mo">=</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">P</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">u</mi>
     <mo class="mo">&gt;</mo>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">u</mi>
      <mn class="mn">0</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo class="mo">∩</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">v</mi>
     <mo class="mo">≤</mo>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">v</mi>
      <mn class="mn">0</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">)</mo>
     <mo class="mo">=</mo>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">v</mi>
      <mn class="mn">0</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo class="mo">−</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">C</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">(</mo>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">u</mi>
      <mn class="mn">0</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">v</mi>
      <mn class="mn">0</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
  <label class="label">(3)</label>
 </disp-formula>
</p>
